"1\n&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by the Mayor of London (FDC29)&#xa0;Introduction \n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nExecutive summary\n&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nPart 1: Concept&#xa0;How ‘devolved’ areas would be defined geographically and set up&#xa0;&#xa0;\nHow public services, including employment, skills and welfare, should be organised to complement devolution&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHow ‘devolved’ areas would be governed, including the role of business in decision making&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nHow ‘devolved’ areas would be held to account&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe strength of the evidence that devolution would lead to economic growth, local improvement and better local governance, including examples of what areas could do with their new powers such as use them to invest in infrastructure and local services&#xa0;\nEconomic \ng\nrowth\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nLocal improvement\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nLocal governance\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe impact on areas not included in any new devolution arrangements, including those on cities’ borders and those affected by resulting changes to national financial equalisation and distributive arrangements&#xa0;Impact on city borders\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nChanges to national financial equalisation and distributive arrangements\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhether reform of the existing system (for example, re-banding council tax, revaluing business rates, Community Budgets, Government grants, formulas and taxes such as stamp duty) would be a precursor to, or run along with, large-scale constitutional change.&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nPart 2: Details&#xa0;What taxes might be devolved—for example council tax, stamp duty and business rates&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat changes should be made to “devolved” authorities’ borrowing powers&#xa0;&#xa0;\nThe scope for areas to introduce new taxes and funding methods such as bonds and crowd-sourcing, fees and charges&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;The extent to which high-performing areas would be expected to redistribute their proceeds of growth via the Treasury&#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;Conclusion&#xa0;&#xa0;Annex 1This table is taken from the LFC report \nRaising the Capital, p25\n.\n&#xa0;Taxation revenue attributable to sub-national and central/federal government as a percentage of GDP, 2010&#xa0;Local governmentState/regional governmentLocal + state/regionalCentral governmentSocial securityTotalCanada\n3.1\n12.2\n15.3\n12.8\n2.8\n31.0\nFrance\n4.6\n0\n4.6\n14.9\n23.2\n42.8\nGermany\n2.8\n7.6\n10.4\n11.3\n14.0\n36.0\nItaly\n6.5\n0\n6.5\n22.7\n13.4\n42.9\nSpain\n3.0\n5.8\n8.8\n11.2\n11.9\n32.2\nSweden\n16.1\n0\n16.1\n23.7\n5.5\n45.5\nUnited Kingdom\n1.7\n0\n1.7\n26.2\n6.6\n34.8\nUnited States\n3.9\n5.0\n9.1\n9.2\n6.3\n24.8\nOECD total (2010)\n3.8\n5.0\n8.8\n20.1\n8.2\n33.7\nSource: OECD \nStats Index\n&#xa0;January 2014\n&#xa0;\n \nThe Mayor\n refer\ns\n the Committee to the \nLFC’s report\n, \nRaising the Capital, \nwhich is available here: \nhttp://www.london.gov.uk/priorities/business-economy/publications/raising-the-capital\n. All \nLFC \nworking papers and the evidence it collected are available \nhere: \nhttp://www.london.gov.uk/london-finance-commission\n.\n \n&#xa0;\n Existing areas of collaboration include local transport schemes, public realm improvements, skills and employment programmes, t\nri-borough arrangements, open data and smart cities, crime prevention and working through the LEP.\n Still, the Mayor\n consider\ns\n Professor Henry Overman’s research about the incentive effect of the devolved business rate, which formed the basis of CLG’s ret\nained business rate policy, of particular relevance to the situation in Lon\ndon. As its focus was London, the Mayor\n also take\ns\n seriously the conclusion of the research conducted by the University of Toronto for the LFC (see p5 for reference), that ‘\nLondon w\nould benefit from greater fiscal autonomy – access to a mix of taxes and the ability to set the tax rates.’\n Mirrlees Review, Tax by Design, Chapter 20, p12. Also see Mirrlees Review, Dimensions of Tax Design, Chapter 8.\n \nDiaz-Serrano, Luis and Rodríguez\n-Pose, Andrés (2012) \nDecentralization, subjective well-being, and the perception of institutions.\n Kyklos, 65 (2). pp. 179-193. ISSN 0023-5962\n,\n \nhttp://eprints.lse.ac.uk/43393/\n \n \nInternational\n Comparison of Global City Financing: A Report to the London Finance Commission prepared by Enid Slack, Institute on Municipal Finance and Governance, Munk School of Global Affairs, University of Toronto, January 2013\n, \nhttp://www.london.gov.uk/sites/default/files/LFC%20International%20comparisons.pdf\n \n \nThe\n Infrastructure Investment\n Plan’s interim report, which will set out deliberations and conclusions to dat\ne, will be published in March 2014 and its final report will follow in summer 2014.\n"